## 🔴 SOC Scenarios Practiced

### Scenario 1 — Identifying Suspicious Processes

**Red flags to look for in `ps aux`:**

| Red Flag | Example | Why Suspicious |
|---|---|---|
| Process running from `/tmp/` | `/tmp/.x` | Malware drops files in /tmp |
| Wrong path for known program | `/tmp/apache2` | Real Apache lives in `/usr/sbin/` |
| High CPU from unknown process | `99.9% /tmp/.update` | Malware often maxes out CPU |
| Hidden filename | `.update` `.x` | Legitimate programs don't hide |

### Scenario 2 — Checking Apache on My Machine

```bash
ps aux | grep "apache"
```

Output:
```
root      1276   /usr/sbin/apache2 -k start    ← root started it (normal)
www-data  1281   /usr/sbin/apache2 -k start    ← www-data runs it (safe)
www-data  1282   /usr/sbin/apache2 -k start    ← multiple workers (normal)
```

**Analysis:**
- ✅ Running from correct path `/usr/sbin/`
- ✅ Operated by `www-data` not root
- ✅ No suspicious behaviour

**If it was malicious it would look like:**
```
root    9999    /tmp/apache2    ← wrong path + wrong user = fake Apache
```

---

## 💡 Most Important Rule Learned Today

> **Always check the FULL PATH of a process — not just the name.**

Malware disguises itself using familiar names like `firefox`, `apache`, `update`.
The path exposes the lie:
- Real Firefox: `/snap/firefox/7967/usr/lib/firefox/firefox`
- Fake Firefox: `/tmp/firefox`

